article.description: Becky Hammon scored 23 points and Shameka Christon added 21 to lead the Liberty to a 72-66 victory over the Mystics.
article.headline: Liberty snap three-game skid, end Mystics' winning streak
article.linkText: Liberty snap three-game skid, end Mystics' win streak
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Liberty finally got a strong all-around effort from start to finish.

Becky Hammon scored 23 points and Shameka Christon added 21 to lead the Liberty to a 72-66 victory over the Washington Mystics on Wednesday night.

Barbara Farris had 11 points and nine rebounds and Loree Moore added a career-high nine rebounds and six assists to help the Liberty (3-9) snap a three-game losing streak.

"We did a better job of taking care of the ball," Hammon said. "We stuck together. There were times where we could have folded it in but we did what we had to do to get the win."

Alana Beard and Chasity Melvin scored 20 points apiece for Washington (7-4), which had its season-high three-game winning streak snapped. The Mystics beat the Liberty twice this season, including a 95-60 win in the season opener May 20.

"They were very efficient tonight in every aspect of the game and there was nothing we could do to stop them," Beard said. "We beat them by 35 in the first game. They're totally a different team. They made changes, they put Loree Moore to the one [point guard] and Becky to the two [shooting guard] and they're playing really well together."

Melvin also had eight rebounds but missed 5-of-11 free throws, including the potential tying attempt with 1:35 left after she was fouled while making a layup. The Liberty then scored the final five points to close the game.

Farris' jumper gave New York a 65-57 lead with 3½ minutes left, before Melvin had a three-point play and Nakia Sanford made a layup to pull Washington within three.

Hammon, who scored 10 points in the fourth quarter, hit two free throws with 2:34 left to stretch the lead to 67-62. Nikki Teasley hit two free throws for the Mystics 18 seconds later and Melvin's layup pulled Washington to 67-66.

"We had some pretty good schemes and we executed a lot better tonight," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said. "We had a couple of mental breakdowns, but fortunately, it wasn't at the end of the game. We never relinquished the lead. Down the stretch we executed better. We made two big stops at the end of the game."

The Mystics opened the scoring on Melvin's layup 1:11 into the game, before the Liberty scored 11 straight points to take the lead for good. Washington got close several times, but New York, which led 32-17 in the second quarter, pulled away each time.

The Mystics, 6-0 at home, have lost four of five on the road.

"When you're on the road, you have to get off to a good start," Washington coach Richie Adubato said. "We're running in mud for some reason. We had our chances, we didn't convert."

Christon made two free throws and hit a 3-pointer to open the third quarter, stretching New York's two-point halftime lead to 39-32.

Latasha Byears and Beard made consecutive layups to get Washington within 43-40 with 3:22 left. The Liberty scored eight straight points, including back-to-back 3s by Hammon and Christon, to push their lead to 51-40 with 1:23 remaining in the third.

The Mystics closed the first half with a 15-2 run over the final 4:45 to pull within 34-32 at the break.

"We did a great job of keeping our composure, especially late in the first half," Christon said. "They came back and made a run, but we kept our composure and kept fighting."

Crystal Robinson, playing at Madison Square Garden as a visiting player for the first time, had five points on 2-for-12 shooting from the field. Robinson, who averaged 10.7 points and 2.8 rebounds in seven seasons with the Liberty before signing with Washington in the offseason, received a nice ovation from the fans during pregame introductions.

Washington was without second-leading scorer DeLisha Milton Jones, who has a sprained ligament in her left knee and will miss six to eight weeks. Milton-Jones, averaging 12.8 points and 3.7 rebounds, injured the knee in the second quarter of Saturday's 88-70 home win over the Liberty.

"She's an Olympian, she's a [veteran]," Beard said. "When you don't have that leadership on the court you're used to having it's tough, but we can't look at that and we can't dwell on it. We have too many other great players on this team who can step up and be efficient on any given night."
